  "summary": "After receiving a letter from Sloane and Reade stating that a painting is not an authentic work by Kip and holds no value, Joyce realizes her last hope for financial stability has vanished. She calls Arthur Harley, who arrives at her house in a car. Harley, a tall man with blue eyes, expresses shock at her impoverished living conditions. Although Joyce admits she does not love him, she agrees to marry him on the condition that she can keep her dog, Trey. Harley agrees and promises to buy her a large ruby ring to contrast with a pearl ring previously given to her by Michael. As Joyce reflects on this decision, she expresses a desire to be forgotten by men and thinks of Michael.\n\nThe following morning, Trey attempts to sunbathe on a rotten windowsill and falls to the street below. Joyce rushes outside to find the injured dog, and an elderly man alights from a taxi to assist her. Suspecting that Trey has internal bleeding, the man helps Joyce load the dog into a taxi to travel to a veterinary station. At the station, a red-faced veterinarian insists that Trey be left for a thorough examination. After leaving the dog, a heartbroken Joyce attempts to walk home, but the elderly man insists on accompanying her to ensure she cleans and bandages a wound Trey caused when he bit her during the transport.",
